# An example of RSA using OpenSSL

1. Let’s create a new message "msg.txt" as per the command below.
`echo '"All paid jobs absorb and degrade the mind." - Aristotle' > msg.txt`[^4]
- Nice one from Aristotle, but no one will work then :)
2. The below is just an example of using openssl to encrypt and decrypt a message, but of course private
key should never be shared and/or exported in a plaintext.

```bash
# *** Generate a pair of keys (public and private) ***
openssl genrsa -out keys.txt 4096
# *** Export the public key from keys.txt ***
openssl rsa -in keys.txt -pubout -out Bob\’s-key.pub
# *** Check Bob’s public key ***
cat Bob-key.pub
# * it should start with -----BEGIN PUBLIC KEY-----
# *** Encrypt msg.txt ***
openssl pkeyutl -in msg.txt -encrypt -pubin -inkey \
Bob-pub-key.key > msg-rsa.enc
# *** Decrypt msg-rsa.enc ***
# *** Step 1 - Export Bob’s private key from keys.txt ***
openssl rsa -in keys.txt -out Bob\’s-private-key.private
# *** Step 2 - Decrypt msg-rsa.enc
openssl pkeyutl -in msg-rsa.enc -decrypt -inkey \
Bob\’s-private-key.private | tee msg-decrypted.txt
```

